The `==` operator and the `.equals()` method in Java are two different ways to compare strings, and choosing the right one depends on the context of what you want to compare.

The `==` operator checks for reference equality. That is, it checks whether both strings are the exact same object in memory. It doesn't compare the content of the strings, but their memory addresses. So if you have two different string objects that contain the same sequence of characters, `==` will return `false` because while the contents are the same, the objects are different.

On the other hand, the `.equals()` method is designed to check the content equality. It compares the value inside each string and checks whether the actual characters are the same in both strings. This is why when you changed one of your string comparisons from `==` to `.equals()`, it fixed your bug. The `.equals()` method ensured that the content of the strings was being compared, not just their reference addresses.

Here's a quick example to illustrate the difference:
```java
String a = new String("Hello");
String b = new String("Hello");
String c = b;

// Reference comparison (memory address)
System.out.println(a == b); // false, because a and b do not refer to the same object
System.out.println(b == c); // true, because b and c refer to the same object

// Content comparison
System.out.println(a.equals(b)); // true, because a and b have the same characters
```

You should use `==` when you want to check if two references point to the same object. This can be useful in certain situations, like checking if a variable is referring to a predefined singleton object or when you're working with enums.

In summary, when comparing strings in Java, always use `.equals()` to compare the content of the strings for logical equality. Use `==` only when you need to check if two references are to the same object, which is a rarer need in typical applications involving string comparison.

